 their part. Moving past "Tiger Mom" stereotypes, he addresses why Asian American and white families practice what he calls "hyper education" and whether or not it makes sense. By taking a behind-the-scenes look at the Scripps National Spelling Bee, other national competitions, and learning centers, Dhingra shows why good schools, good grades, and good behavior are seen as not enough for high-achieving students and their parents and why the education arms race is likely to continue to expand.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAsian American childrenxEducationxSocial aspects. 0aAsian American studentsxPsychology. 0aAsian American studentsxSocial conditions. 0aChildren of immigrantsxEducationxSocial aspects. 0aChildren. 0aCommunities. 0aCommunity life. 0aCompetition. 0aCurriculum enrichmentzUnited States. 0aEmigration and immigration. 0aEquality. 0aEthics. 0aFamilies. 0aFriendship. 0aGifted childrenxEducationzUnited States. 0aIndian American. 0aMathematics. 0aNeoliberalism. 0aNuclear families. 0aParenting. 0aRace. 0aRacism. 0aSchools. 0aSocial media. 0aStudent activitieszUnited States. 0aTiger parents. 0aanti-blackness;Asian American;assimilation. 0aconcerted cultivation. 0adeviance. 0aenrichment education. 0aindigenous pedagogy. 0amedia. 0amodel minority. 0anormative inversion. 0asocial capital. 0aspelling bee. 0astigma. 0asupplemental education. 0awhite supremacy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh  aAsian American.  aIndian American.  aTiger parents.  aanti-blackness.  aassimilation.  achildhood.  acommunity.  acompetition.  aconcerted cultivation.  adeviance.  aenrichment education.  afamily.  afriendship.  aimmigration.  aindigenous pedagogy.  ainequality.  amath.  amedia.